## BlockType Registry Pattern — Already in Spider

```typescript
class BlockTypeRegistry {
  private readonly types = new Map<string, BlockType>();

  register(plugin: LoadedPlugin): void {
    if (isLoadedKit(plugin)) {
      this.registerFromKit(plugin.kit);
    } else if (isLoadedApparatus(plugin)) {
      if (plugin.apparatus.supportKit) {
        this.registerFromKit(plugin.apparatus.supportKit);
      }
    }
  }

  private registerFromKit(kit: Record<string, unknown>): void {
    const raw = kit.blockTypes;
    if (typeof raw !== 'object' || raw === null) return;
    for (const value of Object.values(raw as Record<string, unknown>)) {
      if (isBlockType(value)) {
        this.types.set(value.id, value);
      }
    }
  }

  get(id: string): BlockType | undefined {
    return this.types.get(id);
  }
}
```

Spider startup kit-scanning:
```typescript
// Scan all already-loaded kits for block types.
for (const kit of g.kits()) {
  blockTypeRegistry.register(kit);
}

// Subscribe to plugin:initialized for apparatus supportKits.
ctx.on('plugin:initialized', (plugin: unknown) => {
  const loaded = plugin as LoadedPlugin;
  if (isLoadedApparatus(loaded)) {
    blockTypeRegistry.register(loaded);
  }
});
```

**Note:** The Spider's blockType scanning only handles apparatus in `plugin:initialized` (not kits). This differs from the Loom's Phase 1b. For the new rig template / mapping / writ type scanning, the same design question arises: do we need a Phase 1b scan of already-started apparatuses?

Given Spider has `requires: ['stacks', 'clerk', 'fabricator']`, those three apparatus start before Spider and their `plugin:initialized` events fire before Spider's `start()`. So Spider would miss their supportKit contributions for `rigTemplates`/`rigTemplateMappings` if it only uses the `plugin:initialized` subscription. A Phase 1b scan is needed for the Spider, same as the Loom.

