## Config Shape Reference

### Current guild.json spider section

```json
{
  "spider": {
    "rigTemplates": {
      "mandate": {
        "engines": [
          { "id": "draft", "designId": "draft", "givens": { "writ": "$writ" } },
          { "id": "implement", "designId": "implement", "upstream": ["draft"], "givens": { "writ": "$writ", "role": "$vars.role" } }
        ]
      },
      "default": {
        "engines": [...]
      }
    },
    "variables": {
      "role": "artificer"
    }
  }
}
```

In the current model, `rigTemplates` keys are writ type names (e.g., `"mandate"`) or `"default"`. There is no separate mapping concept — keys serve as both template names and writ-type→template mappings simultaneously.

The brief introduces a separation:
- Template names (e.g., `"audit"` contributed by `quality-tools` → qualified as `"quality-tools.audit"`)
- Writ type → template name mappings (e.g., `"quality-audit"` → `"quality-tools.audit"`)
- Guild config `spider.rigTemplates` keys are unqualified and still work as before (they act as both template definitions AND mappings)
- Guild config may also need `spider.rigTemplateMappings` to allow overriding kit-contributed mappings without redefining the template

### Current guild.json clerk section

```json
{
  "clerk": {
    "writTypes": [
      { "name": "task", "description": "A concrete unit of implementation work" },
      { "name": "bug", "description": "A defect to be fixed" }
    ],
    "defaultType": "mandate"
  }
}
```

